data.statement: Triadic price-bracket videos that explicitly frame a popular fast-food item as 'Cheapest vs. Most Expensive vs. Homemade' (often with 'Challenge' in the title) significantly outperform baseline because the three-way contrast amplifies curiosity (price anchoring + DIY control), taps broad search intent around familiar foods, and promises a clear narrative arc that sustains watch-time.
data.reasoning: This title uses a proven curiosity structure: extreme price anchors ('Cheapest' vs. 'Most Expensive') plus a relatable control ('Homemade'). The three-way contrast creates immediate stakes and clear questions (Is homemade better than the priciest option? How big is the value gap?), increasing CTR. Featuring a mass-market staple (fish sandwich) broadens addressable interest via familiarity and seasonal curiosity, while 'Challenge' signals gamified stakes and outcome uncertainty, supporting retention. The format is repeatable across items (burgers, pizza, nuggets) and testable by comparing similarly structured titles to channel baselines.
